WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:03.212
Jackson:
Last day of training.

00:03.212 --> 00:04.379
Last day of Tim
barking orders.

00:04.379 --> 00:06.840
Last day that they can fire us
at a moment's notice.

00:06.840 --> 00:09.927
Last day of them recording
every flaw for posterity.

00:09.927 --> 00:11.553
It's kind of
bittersweet.

00:11.553 --> 00:12.930
Nope.
Just sweet.

00:12.930 --> 00:14.640
[ Chuckles ]
Sorry. Sorry.

00:14.640 --> 00:16.141
Guys,
stop apologizing.

00:16.141 --> 00:18.227
You guys have
finally made it,

00:18.227 --> 00:19.186
and I will be
right behind you.

00:19.186 --> 00:20.729
Look, the extra month
will fly by.

00:20.729 --> 00:22.022
You know it.

00:22.022 --> 00:24.191
Now, is Tim gonna do
anything special

00:24.191 --> 00:26.485
to memorialize
your last shift together?

00:26.485 --> 00:27.694
Not knowingly.

00:27.694 --> 00:28.612
You know,
when you move on

00:28.612 --> 00:30.614
from an important
relationship,

00:30.614 --> 00:34.451
there are steps you should take
to ensure a healthy parting.

00:34.451 --> 00:37.204
We are going to work through
every single one of them.

00:37.204 --> 00:39.122
Uh, how, if he doesn't know
you're doing it?

00:39.122 --> 00:41.083
Trickery.
Bye.

00:41.083 --> 00:43.669
That's...
Yeah.

00:43.669 --> 00:44.753
Who are <i>you</i> gonna ride with
today?

00:44.753 --> 00:46.171
No idea.

00:46.171 --> 00:48.507
Grey's busy, and Smitty's
getting a back tattoo.

00:48.507 --> 00:50.342
That's ‐‐
Yeah. Don't ask.

00:50.342 --> 00:52.469
So, we are out of TOs,
and I'm guessing

00:52.469 --> 00:54.054
I'm finishing my rookie year
at the front desk.

00:54.054 --> 00:55.180
Huh.
Lopez: Boot.

00:57.432 --> 00:58.642
Where's our gear?

00:58.642 --> 01:00.727
Wait, what?

01:00.727 --> 01:02.604
We started this journey
together.

01:02.604 --> 01:03.981
I think we should end it
that way.

01:03.981 --> 01:05.190
Don't you?

01:05.190 --> 01:06.191
Yeah.

01:06.191 --> 01:07.776
Then let's go.

01:07.776 --> 01:11.655
♪♪

01:11.655 --> 01:13.031
I thought we were tight.

01:13.031 --> 01:14.116
You did?

01:14.116 --> 01:15.158
Um, we are.

01:15.158 --> 01:17.077
That's ‐‐
I mean, why? What?

01:17.077 --> 01:18.704
You told
your ethics professor

01:18.704 --> 01:20.330
she should come for
a ride along?

01:20.330 --> 01:21.331
No.

01:21.331 --> 01:22.332
Mm.
We ‐‐ No.

01:22.332 --> 01:23.834
We didn't even,
uh, discuss it,

01:23.834 --> 01:25.419
but I‐I need to
pass this class,

01:25.419 --> 01:28.589
so it's super important
she doesn't get shot today.

01:28.589 --> 01:29.881
No promises.

01:29.881 --> 01:31.508
You ride with me, you ride
the roller coaster.

01:31.508 --> 01:33.093
Okay, Nyla, I know that ‐‐

01:33.093 --> 01:34.886
Hi. Good morning.
Good morning.

01:34.886 --> 01:36.972
Uh, Professor Ryan, this is
Detective Nyla Harper,

01:36.972 --> 01:38.181
my training officer.

01:38.181 --> 01:39.099
I'm told
you're gonna be going

01:39.099 --> 01:40.559
on a ride along
with us today.

01:40.559 --> 01:42.185
I hope that's okay.

01:42.185 --> 01:44.604
I didn't want to put you in an
awkward position by asking you,

01:44.604 --> 01:46.523
but your watch commander said
that you'd feel cheated

01:46.523 --> 01:47.858
if I didn't
ride with you, so...

01:47.858 --> 01:49.651
And he was right.

01:49.651 --> 01:50.777
[ Chuckles ]

01:50.777 --> 01:51.737
Uh, shall we?
Mm.

01:51.737 --> 01:53.947
Okay.

01:53.947 --> 01:55.741
Harper: So, you, uh,
sign all the paperwork

01:55.741 --> 01:57.117
that says that
we are not liable

01:57.117 --> 01:58.910
if you are maimed
or killed?

01:58.910 --> 02:00.537
I did. It seemed
a bit excessive.

02:00.537 --> 02:01.955
Mm.
No, it's not.

02:01.955 --> 02:03.790
I mean, we will try our best
to protect you,

02:03.790 --> 02:06.501
but we cannot guarantee
your safety.

02:06.501 --> 02:09.713
You will be exposed to all
the same dangers that we are.

02:09.713 --> 02:13.175
Well, more farmers die yearly
than cops do.

02:13.175 --> 02:14.635
I didn't have to sign
a liability waiver

02:14.635 --> 02:16.094
to go apple picking.

02:16.094 --> 02:17.638
That's because you weren't
picking them

02:17.638 --> 02:18.680
out of a wood chipper.

02:18.680 --> 02:19.890
Nolan: Uh, hey,

02:19.890 --> 02:21.475
have you ever seen
a body camera up close?

02:21.475 --> 02:22.601
No.

02:22.601 --> 02:23.977
Well, they're
always running,

02:23.977 --> 02:26.188
uh, until
we actually need them.

02:26.188 --> 02:27.522
We switch them on,
then they start recording,

02:27.522 --> 02:28.815
and they go back
two minutes

02:28.815 --> 02:30.275
so we can catch any of that
last‐minute action.

02:30.275 --> 02:32.402
Oh, yet they're
always broken

02:32.402 --> 02:34.446
whenever the cops
cross the line.

02:34.446 --> 02:36.490
You'd be surprised
how many police officers

02:36.490 --> 02:38.617
actually <i>want</i>
a body camera.

02:38.617 --> 02:39.951
Oh.
That way,

02:39.951 --> 02:41.828
it makes it easier to
disprove complaints.

02:41.828 --> 02:44.373
Okay,
then you will not mind

02:44.373 --> 02:46.917
if I record
the ride along myself ‐‐

02:46.917 --> 02:47.876
as research tool.

02:47.876 --> 02:48.669
No problem.

02:50.003 --> 02:51.588
[ Chuckles ]

02:51.588 --> 02:53.465
Just as long as you
turn it off

02:53.465 --> 02:55.967
when we hit the strip club
for the lunch buffet.

02:58.804 --> 03:00.055
She's kidding.

03:00.055 --> 03:02.265
That buffet is terrible
at that strip club.

03:02.265 --> 03:03.892
♪ Whoa, oh, oh, oh ♪
Ready to go?

03:03.892 --> 03:06.061
♪ Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

03:06.061 --> 03:10.857
♪ I'm gonna win for you
like I know you want me to do ♪

03:10.857 --> 03:12.109
[ Cameras beeping ]

03:12.109 --> 03:13.568
You got yours on?
Yeah.

03:13.568 --> 03:15.237
Alright.

03:15.237 --> 03:16.822
It's our last shift
together.

03:16.822 --> 03:18.073
It's crazy, huh?

03:18.073 --> 03:19.574
Not really.

03:19.574 --> 03:20.951
Come on.

03:20.951 --> 03:22.202
I mean, we've been riding
shoulder to shoulder

03:22.202 --> 03:23.620
for over a year now.
[ Engine starts ]

03:23.620 --> 03:25.664
And soon, there'll be a new
rookie sitting in that seat,

03:25.664 --> 03:28.250
annoying the crap out of me
for 12 hours a day.

03:28.250 --> 03:31.128
So, you're not gonna miss
riding with me at all?

03:31.128 --> 03:32.838
It's a job,
not happy hour.

03:32.838 --> 03:35.090
Mm. Denial. Check.

03:36.383 --> 03:37.676
What?
Hmm?

03:37.676 --> 03:38.802
Nothing.

03:38.802 --> 03:45.434
♪♪

03:46.476 --> 03:49.271
So, you teach
full time?

03:49.271 --> 03:51.815
No. Just nights
and weekends.

03:51.815 --> 03:54.359
My day job is
civil rights litigation.

03:54.359 --> 03:56.194
And then there's lecturing,
the writing,

03:56.194 --> 03:57.529
the cable news hits.

03:57.529 --> 03:58.530
When do you sleep?

03:58.530 --> 03:59.990
Sleep?
What's that?

03:59.990 --> 04:01.825
Oh, is that what you were doing
in my class on Monday?

04:01.825 --> 04:03.743
[ Chuckles ]
What?

04:03.743 --> 04:04.703
No. Uh, no.

04:04.703 --> 04:05.871
Sometimes, I just ‐‐
I hold a blink

04:05.871 --> 04:07.706
for a really long time.

04:07.706 --> 04:09.458
You sure lying to your teacher
is the way to go here?

04:09.458 --> 04:10.584
Actually, now that
I hear it out loud,

04:10.584 --> 04:11.710
I'd like to revise my answer.

04:11.710 --> 04:13.587
Yeah. Uh‐huh.
[ Chuckles ]

04:13.587 --> 04:15.589
So, uh, given how busy
you are,

04:15.589 --> 04:17.757
why take the time
for a ride along?

04:17.757 --> 04:20.760
Well, I'm finishing up a book
on the future of policing.

04:20.760 --> 04:23.722
Hey, what would you say is
the, uh, biggest challenge

04:23.722 --> 04:26.057
you face day to day?

04:26.057 --> 04:28.185
Finding
a safe bathroom.

04:28.185 --> 04:29.561
Uh, that is ‐‐
that is true.

04:29.561 --> 04:32.022
I mean, we can't use a stall
bathroom for safety reasons.

04:32.022 --> 04:33.732
The door has to go
floor to ceiling.

04:33.732 --> 04:35.734
And the location of the
bathroom, also very important,

04:35.734 --> 04:37.903
so that not a lot of people
can see us entering and leaving.

04:37.903 --> 04:39.196
[ Radio static crackles ]

04:39.196 --> 04:40.572
Dispatch: <i>7‐Adam‐15,</i>

04:40.572 --> 04:43.700
<i>residential burglary alarm,</i>
<i>1330 Monrovia.</i>

04:43.700 --> 04:45.702
Hundred bucks it's
an accidental trigger.

04:45.702 --> 04:47.078
That is a hard pass.

04:47.078 --> 04:48.997
[ Chuckles ]
She's ‐‐ She's kidding.

04:48.997 --> 04:50.707
No. No way we'd blow off
a service call.

04:50.707 --> 04:51.708
[ Radio beeps ]

04:51.708 --> 04:53.418
Copy. Responding.

04:53.418 --> 04:54.503
[ Static crackles ]

04:54.503 --> 04:55.962
Lucy: Do you see yourself
as my mentor?

04:57.130 --> 04:59.257
No. I'm your TO.

04:59.257 --> 05:01.760
It's my job to make sure you're
not dangerously incompetent

05:01.760 --> 05:04.638
when you hit the streets without
supervision tomorrow.

05:04.638 --> 05:05.806
You know,
when I was a rookie,

05:05.806 --> 05:06.932
I couldn't wait
to get off probation.

05:06.932 --> 05:08.725
Oh, I am excited.

05:08.725 --> 05:10.435
Believe me.

05:10.435 --> 05:13.730
But I also know the importance
of acknowledging your loss

05:13.730 --> 05:15.816
when going through
something like this.

05:15.816 --> 05:17.108
"Acknowledging
your loss"?

05:17.108 --> 05:18.568
Hmm.

05:18.568 --> 05:21.071
What is this, some
"Intro to Psych" closure BS?

05:21.071 --> 05:22.864
It's not BS.

05:22.864 --> 05:24.825
It's a widely used
psychological model

05:24.825 --> 05:27.410
to help people cope with
the end of a relationship.

05:27.410 --> 05:28.912
Relationship?

05:28.912 --> 05:31.164
Partnership.
Mentorship.

05:31.164 --> 05:32.332
Whatever you want to
call it.

05:32.332 --> 05:33.625
Look, I don't want to
call it anything.

05:33.625 --> 05:35.627
It's not like you won't see me
tomorrow at the station.

05:35.627 --> 05:37.420
You know, what's there
to talk about?

05:37.420 --> 05:38.880
A lot.

05:38.880 --> 05:40.799
I have a list.

05:40.799 --> 05:42.133
So...
A list?

05:44.427 --> 05:47.180
You know, littering is
a $250 fine.

05:47.180 --> 05:49.558
Worth it.

05:49.558 --> 05:50.976
What are you smiling
about?

05:50.976 --> 05:53.979
Well, we were at denial,

05:53.979 --> 05:57.107
but now we have moved
to anger.

05:57.107 --> 05:58.483
That's more progress.

06:02.779 --> 06:03.780
Thank you.

06:03.780 --> 06:05.907
[ Radio chatter ]

06:05.907 --> 06:07.158
Gets me out of
the office.

06:07.158 --> 06:08.827
I mean,
not just for today.

06:08.827 --> 06:10.245
I mean, you could have
bounced me from the program

06:10.245 --> 06:12.414
after that first day.

06:12.414 --> 06:13.832
I owe you my career.

06:13.832 --> 06:15.500
♪ I confess,
don't hate the playa... ♪

06:15.500 --> 06:17.377
I'd settle for a sandwich.
We're near Phillipe's.

06:17.377 --> 06:19.004
But you just
had breakfast.

06:19.004 --> 06:20.463
You questioning
the pregnant lady?

06:20.463 --> 06:21.840
[ Chuckling ] No, ma'am.
No, ma'am.

06:21.840 --> 06:23.133
What?

06:24.342 --> 06:25.802
You're gonna be a mom.

06:26.553 --> 06:28.805
And?

06:28.805 --> 06:30.473
I don't know.
I mean...

06:30.473 --> 06:33.602
a lot's happened since
we started out together.

06:33.602 --> 06:35.729
I knew my TO would be
important to my career,

06:35.729 --> 06:38.064
but...I don't know.

06:38.064 --> 06:39.774
I didn't realize how important
you'd be to my life.

06:39.774 --> 06:41.401
♪ They might shine,
but when they lights go out... ♪

06:41.401 --> 06:43.820
Lay off the sappy stuff.
I'm nauseous enough as it is.

06:43.820 --> 06:45.280
[ Chuckles ]

06:47.490 --> 06:48.366
Fiona: Have you read
my work?

06:49.534 --> 06:51.036
I have.

06:51.036 --> 06:52.579
I actually follow you
on social media.

06:52.579 --> 06:54.581
Oh. And?

06:54.581 --> 06:57.667
I'd make a lot of the reforms
you're pushing for,

06:57.667 --> 06:59.878
but some just aren't
based in reality.

06:59.878 --> 07:02.297
Well, maybe not
your reality.

07:02.297 --> 07:04.257
Look, either you want
my opinion or you don't.

07:04.257 --> 07:07.052
If you are just here to confirm
your own point of view,

07:07.052 --> 07:08.386
then I‐I will stop
engaging.

07:08.386 --> 07:09.721
No, no, no, no.
That's not what I'm looking for.

07:09.721 --> 07:12.057
I‐I'm just used to cops
taking my head off

07:12.057 --> 07:13.975
any time I suggest
changing the status quo.

07:13.975 --> 07:15.477
So...
Well, you would be
surprised

07:15.477 --> 07:17.687
how many cops actually know
the system has to change,

07:17.687 --> 07:19.648
but just feel powerless
to make it happen.

07:19.648 --> 07:21.066
Hmm.

07:21.066 --> 07:22.984
[ Door closes ]

07:22.984 --> 07:24.736
Homeowner set off the alarm
accidentally.

07:24.736 --> 07:25.695
Hundred bucks.

07:25.695 --> 07:26.946
Just put it on my tab.

07:26.946 --> 07:28.782
So, you two
getting along? Huh?

07:28.782 --> 07:29.824
My two teachers?

07:29.824 --> 07:30.909
Mm.
Yeah.

07:30.909 --> 07:32.369
We're bonding
by making fun of you.

07:32.369 --> 07:34.412
Oh. Outstanding.
Let me get in on that.

07:34.412 --> 07:35.205
Have you noticed
how much I've been

07:35.205 --> 07:37.040
saying "like" lately?

07:37.040 --> 07:39.292
[ Alarm beeping ]

07:39.292 --> 07:40.335
Child abduction.

07:40.335 --> 07:42.504
Suspect is driving
a gold Tacoma truck.

07:42.504 --> 07:43.797
Plate number

07:43.797 --> 07:46.716
2‐Queen‐Robert‐Ida‐4‐4‐5.

07:46.716 --> 07:47.717
Victim was kidnapped from...

07:47.717 --> 07:49.302
City of Angels Hospital.

07:49.302 --> 07:50.762
How old?

07:50.762 --> 07:52.889
Uh...five hours.

07:57.018 --> 07:58.019
Here we go.

07:58.019 --> 08:00.063
[ Engine starts ]

08:00.063 --> 08:03.149
[ Rotor blades whirring ]

08:03.149 --> 08:04.234
Air Three
is lifting now.

08:04.234 --> 08:05.360
I'm 10‐9‐7.

08:05.360 --> 08:08.446
Searching for
the suspect vehicle.

08:08.446 --> 08:11.408
Uh, newborn baby girl
went missing 20 minutes ago.

08:11.408 --> 08:13.576
The hospital is going over
the surveillance footage.

08:13.576 --> 08:15.453
Wait, don't all babies
get LoJack these days?

08:15.453 --> 08:17.706
Yeah, it was found in
the elevator, cut off.

08:17.706 --> 08:19.374
Who owns the Tacoma?

08:19.374 --> 08:21.793
Uh, that would be
the father ‐‐ Jared Young.

08:21.793 --> 08:23.545
Looks like they're going through
a messy divorce.

08:23.545 --> 08:25.797
He was visiting the hospital
earlier that day,

08:25.797 --> 08:27.340
but security had him leave.

08:27.340 --> 08:28.758
There may have been
some kind of threat.

08:28.758 --> 08:30.593
So, what, he went back in
and he just took the baby?

08:30.593 --> 08:32.470
Jared's got quite an extensive
criminal history here.

08:32.470 --> 08:34.389
Lot of narcos ‐‐
uh, narco possession,

08:34.389 --> 08:36.683
possession to sell,
under the influence.

08:36.683 --> 08:38.435
Mm, just the guy you want
taking care of your newborn.

08:38.435 --> 08:39.769
Well, we got the whole city
looking for him.

08:39.769 --> 08:40.770
He won't get far.

08:40.770 --> 08:43.189
So, this baby that the, uh,

08:43.189 --> 08:44.733
whole city is mobilized
to find ‐‐

08:44.733 --> 08:46.151
is she by any chance white?

08:47.569 --> 08:49.112
We issue plenty of
Amber Alerts

08:49.112 --> 08:50.530
for children of color,
as well.

08:52.198 --> 08:53.324
Do you have a kid?

08:53.324 --> 08:54.993
Daughter.

08:54.993 --> 08:56.369
And, uh, you're sure
your daughter

08:56.369 --> 08:58.163
would get the same attention
as his son?

08:58.997 --> 09:00.707
From the media? No.

09:00.707 --> 09:04.669
But out here, we ‐‐
we look just as hard.

09:04.669 --> 09:06.421
Mrs. Young,
this is Detective Lopez.

09:06.421 --> 09:08.339
I'm out here
searching for your baby.

09:08.339 --> 09:09.507
Mrs. Young: [ Voice breaking ]
<i>You have to find her.</i>

09:09.507 --> 09:10.800
Yes, ma'am,
we're doing everything we can,

09:10.800 --> 09:12.302
but I need your help.

09:12.302 --> 09:14.095
Is there any place your husband
might take her?

09:14.095 --> 09:15.305
<i>He lives in Bell Gardens.</i>

09:15.305 --> 09:16.556
Yes, ma'am.

09:16.556 --> 09:18.266
We have officers on the way
to his apartment now,

09:18.266 --> 09:21.102
but if he's not there,
where would he be?

09:21.102 --> 09:23.938
<i>Out buying drugs,</i>
<i>if he has any money.</i>

09:23.938 --> 09:25.482
And if he's not?

09:25.482 --> 09:27.609
<i>Jared will do anything</i>
<i>to get a fix,</i>

09:27.609 --> 09:30.111
<i>including selling our baby.</i>

09:30.111 --> 09:31.362
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

09:33.782 --> 09:35.283
Gold pickup,
two blocks up.

09:35.283 --> 09:36.242
[ Tires squealing,
engine revving ]

09:36.242 --> 09:39.954
♪♪

09:39.954 --> 09:42.165
Negative.
Texas plates.

09:43.541 --> 09:44.709
Five hours old.

09:44.709 --> 09:46.294
That poor mother must be
going out of her mind.

09:48.338 --> 09:49.255
Let me guess ‐‐

09:49.255 --> 09:50.882
you think if the parents
had properly

09:50.882 --> 09:52.383
worked through
their separation,

09:52.383 --> 09:53.676
this whole thing
could have been avoided?

09:53.676 --> 09:57.597
No. Mom needs to get as far away
from him as possible.

09:57.597 --> 09:59.933
But I do think that having
easier access

09:59.933 --> 10:01.392
to counseling
and mental health resources

10:01.392 --> 10:03.019
could prevent
situations like this.

10:03.019 --> 10:05.355
Sure. But most guys
still wouldn't go.

10:05.355 --> 10:06.940
Yeah, because we stigmatize
mental health,

10:06.940 --> 10:09.651
treat it as less important
than physical health.

10:09.651 --> 10:11.444
It's ridiculous that they teach
sex ed in schools,

10:11.444 --> 10:13.947
but not how to be
in a relationship.

10:13.947 --> 10:15.532
I wish someone taught me
how to be in this one.

10:15.532 --> 10:17.033
Oh, so we <i>are</i>
in a relationship.

10:19.285 --> 10:21.162
So, what's the focus
of your book?

10:21.162 --> 10:23.248
Uh, reinventing policing ‐‐

10:23.248 --> 10:24.874
with a more limited
mandate.

10:24.874 --> 10:26.459
Amen to that.

10:26.459 --> 10:28.586
You agree with taking resources
away from police?

10:28.586 --> 10:31.256
If it lessens our load,
then yes, absolutely.

10:31.256 --> 10:33.091
Yeah, we complain about it
all the time.

10:33.091 --> 10:35.343
Police have become the catch‐all
for the city's problems.

10:35.343 --> 10:39.889
We're expected to be cops,
uh, psychologists,

10:39.889 --> 10:42.475
social workers, teachers,
mediators.

10:42.475 --> 10:44.227
And they only train us
for one of those jobs.

10:44.227 --> 10:46.271
Gold truck.
Two cars ahead.

10:46.271 --> 10:47.021
That's him.

10:48.898 --> 10:50.150
Control, 7‐Adam‐15.

10:50.150 --> 10:52.443
We have eyes on
the Amber Alert suspect vehicle.

10:52.443 --> 10:54.779
Heading west on Pico,
passing Westlake.

10:54.779 --> 10:57.824
7‐Adam‐19, inbound on Olympic,
passing Ardmore.

10:57.824 --> 11:00.285
7‐Adam‐07, coming west from
Wilshire and Rimpau ‐‐

11:00.285 --> 11:01.744
moving to intercept
from the front.

11:01.744 --> 11:03.913
Air Three responding.
Heading west from Bell Gardens.

11:03.913 --> 11:06.457
ETA to your location ‐‐
approximately six minutes.

11:06.457 --> 11:08.334
Can you parallel suspect
until I get eyes on?

11:08.334 --> 11:09.502
Affirmative.

11:09.502 --> 11:10.712
Parallel?

11:10.712 --> 11:12.338
Yeah, we follow on side streets
and alleyways.

11:14.674 --> 11:16.092
Oh, so he doesn't spot you
and run?

11:16.092 --> 11:17.594
Exactly.
Last thing we want

11:17.594 --> 11:19.262
is him speeding through traffic
with a baby in the car,

11:19.262 --> 11:20.305
especially since
there's no way

11:20.305 --> 11:21.806
he's got an infant car seat
in there.

11:21.806 --> 11:23.224
No, we'll just wait until
we have enough units,

11:23.224 --> 11:24.350
and then we'll
box him in.

11:24.350 --> 11:26.311
Intersection ahead.
We still have him?

11:26.311 --> 11:27.729
Yeah, he's about half a car
length ahead,

11:27.729 --> 11:28.897
but he's speeding up.

11:28.897 --> 11:30.607
He might've seen us
before we made our turn.

11:30.607 --> 11:32.400
♪♪

11:32.400 --> 11:34.402
7‐Adam‐19,
Maxwell and Pico.

11:34.402 --> 11:36.112
West of target ‐‐
waiting for him to pass.

11:39.824 --> 11:42.285
Suspect just went past.
Speed ‐‐ 50 miles an hour.

11:42.285 --> 11:43.494
We'll move to parallel
on the north.

11:43.494 --> 11:44.704
Copy that.

11:44.704 --> 11:45.997
Why not just set up
a roadblock?

11:45.997 --> 11:47.624
Roadblocks are considered
a lethal measure.

11:47.624 --> 11:48.625
Didn't know that.

11:48.625 --> 11:49.709
Yeah,
there's a strong chance

11:49.709 --> 11:51.544
a desperate driver
will ram a roadblock.

11:51.544 --> 11:52.712
Clear!

11:52.712 --> 11:54.339
We don't use them unless
we have no other choice.

11:54.339 --> 11:55.632
Come on, come on.
Watch out, watch out!

11:55.632 --> 11:57.217
[ Tires screech ]

11:57.217 --> 11:57.967
I can't see
around the truck.

11:57.967 --> 11:59.177
Move it!
I got it.

11:59.177 --> 12:00.386
Move! Hey!
I got it after this car.

12:00.386 --> 12:02.513
Hold on. There we go.
Got it.

12:04.974 --> 12:07.060
Do you see him?
No.

12:07.060 --> 12:09.437
Well, maybe ‐‐ maybe he turned
around when we got stuck.

12:09.437 --> 12:11.105
7‐Adam‐19,
we've lost visual.

12:11.105 --> 12:12.440
You got eyes on him?

12:12.440 --> 12:14.359
Negative.
We haven't reacquired visual.

12:14.359 --> 12:16.319
Where the hell
is that airship?

12:16.319 --> 12:18.446
Pilot: Air Three is overhead.
Arriving on scene.

12:18.446 --> 12:20.240
What's the suspect's 20?

12:20.240 --> 12:22.242
We lost visual.
Pico, east of Maxwell.

12:22.242 --> 12:24.494
It's possible he turned off and
headed either north or south.

12:24.494 --> 12:26.120
Copy that.
We're gonna orbit.

12:26.120 --> 12:31.084
♪♪

12:31.084 --> 12:32.669
Contact.

12:32.669 --> 12:34.504
Suspect vehicle now heading
north on Livingston.

12:34.504 --> 12:36.172
Repeat,
north on Livingston.

12:36.172 --> 12:37.882
Copy. On our way.

12:37.882 --> 12:40.218
Speed is
approximately 65.

12:40.218 --> 12:41.261
Looks like he's heading
for the freeway.

12:41.261 --> 12:43.596
[ Tires screech ]

12:46.182 --> 12:47.267
Hold on.

12:47.267 --> 12:49.018
Suspect just sideswiped
another vehicle.

12:49.018 --> 12:50.687
He's lost control.

12:50.687 --> 12:52.897
[ Car crashes ]

12:52.897 --> 12:54.440
Tell me that wasn't
our guy.

12:54.440 --> 12:56.067
<i>He just TC'd into</i>
<i>a telephone pole.</i>

12:56.067 --> 12:58.069
Can you see
inside the truck?

12:58.069 --> 12:59.279
<i>Negative.</i>

13:00.613 --> 13:01.990
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

13:01.990 --> 13:04.158
[ Tires squealing ]

13:08.663 --> 13:09.998
[ Brakes screech ]

13:11.165 --> 13:12.208
Harper: Hands!
Nolan: Police!

13:14.794 --> 13:16.504
Show me your hands!

13:16.504 --> 13:17.714
Where is your daughter?

13:17.714 --> 13:19.215
Jared: What?

13:19.215 --> 13:20.967
Nolan: Keep your hands
where we can see them.

13:25.179 --> 13:26.723
No kid.
There's no kid in here!

13:26.723 --> 13:27.890
There's no kid!

13:27.890 --> 13:29.267
Your baby,
where is she?

13:29.267 --> 13:30.768
At the hospital
with her mom.

13:30.768 --> 13:31.853
Lucy:
Then why did you run?

13:31.853 --> 13:33.354
Tim: Gun and drugs.

13:35.773 --> 13:37.358
Fiona: If he doesn't have
the baby, who does?

13:42.613 --> 13:43.573
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

13:43.573 --> 13:44.991
Never thought
I'd be disappointed

13:44.991 --> 13:47.410
a meth‐head <i>wasn't</i>
taking care of a newborn.

13:47.410 --> 13:48.745
But I guess there's still
plenty of time

13:48.745 --> 13:50.580
for him to mess up
this kid's childhood,

13:50.580 --> 13:51.706
once we get her back.

13:52.874 --> 13:53.958
<i>If</i> we get her back.

13:53.958 --> 13:55.918
[ Radio chatter ]

13:55.918 --> 13:58.296
You know, whenever you need
Halloween costumes

13:58.296 --> 13:59.797
for Lopez Jr.,

13:59.797 --> 14:02.258
my mom has dozens
in storage.

14:02.258 --> 14:05.136
I'm talking cop uniforms
for every age.

14:05.136 --> 14:06.846
You never really wanted to be
anything else?

14:08.681 --> 14:11.059
Astronaut? Ninja?

14:11.059 --> 14:12.435
Ninja astronaut?
[ Chuckles ]

14:12.435 --> 14:15.229
I mean, that'd be cool,
but...mnh‐mnh.

14:15.229 --> 14:16.272
No.

14:16.272 --> 14:18.608
I guess I just
wanted to be my dad.

14:18.608 --> 14:20.735
It was like my way of
feeling close to him

14:20.735 --> 14:21.778
when he wasn't around.

14:21.778 --> 14:23.905
Was that a lot?
Yeah.

14:23.905 --> 14:26.449
I mean, he was a detective
when I was born,

14:26.449 --> 14:28.868
trying to make a name
for himself.

14:28.868 --> 14:30.703
Lot of long hours.

14:30.703 --> 14:31.913
But you were close.

14:31.913 --> 14:33.581
Yeah, eventually.

14:33.581 --> 14:36.501
Mom was kind of on her own
until I was 12.

14:36.501 --> 14:38.795
And that's when he moved up,
got more stable hours.

14:38.795 --> 14:40.546
Mm.

14:40.546 --> 14:43.716
I mean,
I always loved him ‐‐

14:43.716 --> 14:46.469
don't get me wrong ‐‐
even when he wasn't around.

14:46.469 --> 14:49.680
I have a lot of
great memories, you know?

14:49.680 --> 14:51.015
Of course.

14:51.015 --> 14:54.060
You know, you and Wesley are
going to be awesome parents.

14:54.060 --> 14:56.187
I know.

14:56.187 --> 14:57.855
It's just...

14:57.855 --> 14:59.899
We both get so wrapped up
in our cases,

14:59.899 --> 15:03.027
we barely make time
to have dinner together.

15:03.027 --> 15:04.779
How are we supposed to
make time for a kid?

15:04.779 --> 15:07.907
Wesley is loaded.
You get yourself a nanny.

15:07.907 --> 15:09.325
Or three.

15:09.325 --> 15:10.660
So a stranger
can raise my child?

15:10.660 --> 15:11.911
I mean,
it won't be a stranger

15:11.911 --> 15:14.455
when you get to know them,
you know?

15:14.455 --> 15:16.666
Look, you are not
the first detective

15:16.666 --> 15:18.751
to have to balance work
with a kid.

15:18.751 --> 15:20.086
Talk to Harper
about how she did it.

15:21.712 --> 15:24.632
Lopez: <i>Harper, can you ten‐three</i>
<i>to a backup channel?</i>

15:26.342 --> 15:28.928
Sure, go to 11.
Don't record this.

15:29.846 --> 15:31.139
[ Camera clicks off ]

15:33.057 --> 15:35.434
I need you to give me
the reals on something.

15:35.434 --> 15:36.769
How difficult was it
to go back to work

15:36.769 --> 15:38.146
after Lila was born?

15:39.480 --> 15:40.815
Honestly,
I barely remember.

15:40.815 --> 15:42.567
I almost died
giving birth, so...

15:43.651 --> 15:46.529
But, uh, that's ‐‐ that's not
gonna happen to you.

15:46.529 --> 15:50.658
G‐Giving birth can be
a wonderful experience,

15:50.658 --> 15:52.952
I've been told.

15:52.952 --> 15:54.162
Definitely get
the epidural.

15:54.162 --> 15:56.497
Don't worry.
I'm not a lunatic.

15:56.497 --> 15:58.833
I'm thinking of scheduling a C,
but I'm worried

15:58.833 --> 16:00.168
that the stitches
and everything

16:00.168 --> 16:02.712
will keep me off work
even longer.

16:02.712 --> 16:04.547
I worried about the same thing,
but you know what?

16:04.547 --> 16:05.840
I got stitches anyway ‐‐

16:05.840 --> 16:07.675
just not in my stomach.

16:07.675 --> 16:09.302
Okay. Change us back
to channel one.

16:09.302 --> 16:11.179
Wh‐‐ I‐I‐‐ I think
I want to hear this.

16:12.638 --> 16:14.390
Tell me the truth ‐‐

16:14.390 --> 16:16.267
Am I gonna poop myself?

16:16.267 --> 16:17.977
And I'm out.

16:17.977 --> 16:19.103
Wow.

16:19.103 --> 16:20.229
[ Chuckles ]

16:20.229 --> 16:21.898
I wish I could say no.

16:21.898 --> 16:23.816
Why can't we just do that
twilight sleep thing

16:23.816 --> 16:25.234
they did back in the '50s?

16:25.234 --> 16:26.694
[ Chuckles ]
I asked.

16:26.694 --> 16:29.447
Apparently it is
"grossly unethical."

16:29.447 --> 16:32.158
Sgt. Grey: <i>Detectives,</i>
<i>are you done?</i>

16:32.158 --> 16:33.117
Both: Yes, sir.

16:38.206 --> 16:41.334
We must seem callous,
joking while a kid is missing.

16:41.334 --> 16:42.627
No, I get it.
I'm sure it's hard

16:42.627 --> 16:44.670
to work
these kinds of cases.

16:44.670 --> 16:46.380
Calls involving kids
are the worst.

16:46.380 --> 16:47.757
You can't help but think,
what if they were mine?

16:47.757 --> 16:48.841
Mm.

16:48.841 --> 16:49.884
Yeah,
I don't have kids,

16:49.884 --> 16:51.928
but I feel the same way

16:51.928 --> 16:54.096
every time another Black kid
gets shot by police.

16:55.932 --> 16:57.558
[ Computer beeps ]

16:58.517 --> 17:01.145
Oh. Hospital sent
the video of the kidnapping.

17:02.939 --> 17:04.315
You can't see her face.

17:06.108 --> 17:07.526
Lopez:
That is just terrifying.

17:07.526 --> 17:09.528
A stranger
snatching your baby

17:09.528 --> 17:10.738
when you're not there
to protect them.

17:10.738 --> 17:11.948
Don't worry.

17:11.948 --> 17:13.658
I will personally
stand watch over your kid

17:13.658 --> 17:14.825
until you leave
the hospital.

17:14.825 --> 17:16.369
You better.

17:16.369 --> 17:18.037
Do they have an ID
on the kidnapper?

17:18.037 --> 17:18.955
Not yet.

17:18.955 --> 17:20.331
Listen to me.

17:20.331 --> 17:23.251
We're gonna find her,
alright?

17:23.251 --> 17:24.752
And that baby's
gonna be fine.

17:24.752 --> 17:26.045
You'll see.

17:26.045 --> 17:29.298
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

17:31.384 --> 17:32.677
We don't have time
for this.

17:32.677 --> 17:35.012
Every minute we waste waiting
for an ID on this woman

17:35.012 --> 17:36.514
is a minute she could be
hurting this kid ‐‐

17:36.514 --> 17:37.890
or worse.

17:37.890 --> 17:38.891
Look, you need to
get your head right

17:38.891 --> 17:39.850
in case this goes bad.

17:39.850 --> 17:41.727
I'm squared away.

17:41.727 --> 17:44.689
The fact that you just said that
means you're not.

17:45.982 --> 17:47.650
Look, you've been lucky
on the job so far.

17:49.193 --> 17:51.195
No. Alright.

17:51.195 --> 17:54.115
I'm sorry. That ‐‐
That came out wrong.

17:54.115 --> 17:55.449
You've been through Hell ‐‐

17:55.449 --> 17:58.119
stuff that would've broken
a lot of veteran cops.

17:58.119 --> 18:00.663
But a dead kid
is different.

18:00.663 --> 18:03.583
A dead kid
changes you forever.

18:05.084 --> 18:06.335
[ Sighs ]

18:06.335 --> 18:08.796
I really hope
our last shift together

18:08.796 --> 18:10.089
doesn't end with that.

18:10.089 --> 18:12.800
Yeah. Me too.

18:12.800 --> 18:14.093
[ Radio chatter ]

18:14.093 --> 18:16.053
Okay, so what's next
on your list?

18:19.181 --> 18:22.893
[ Inhales sharply ]
Okay.

18:22.893 --> 18:24.270
"Surround yourself with people

18:24.270 --> 18:26.772
who support, value,
and energize you,"

18:26.772 --> 18:29.900
which...may have to wait
until later.

18:29.900 --> 18:32.486
Then, uh, "Reflect on
the lessons learned ‐‐

18:32.486 --> 18:36.073
both the good and the bad ‐‐
and express gratitude."

18:37.366 --> 18:39.535
Okay.

18:39.535 --> 18:42.163
So, what have I taught you
that you're grateful for?

18:42.163 --> 18:44.165
Um...hmm.

18:46.000 --> 18:48.836
Not to second‐guess
myself.

18:48.836 --> 18:50.880
Yeah, early on,

18:50.880 --> 18:54.050
one look from you
could send me into a tailspin.

18:54.050 --> 18:55.468
Plain Clothes Day.
Mm‐hmm.

18:55.468 --> 18:57.511
But I've learned to trust
my instincts,

18:57.511 --> 19:00.306
even if they go against
what you would do,

19:00.306 --> 19:02.433
which will be crucial
for undercover work.

19:04.352 --> 19:06.395
You serious about
being UC?

19:06.395 --> 19:08.564
Yeah.

19:08.564 --> 19:10.358
Why? Do you not think
I'm tough enough?

19:10.358 --> 19:12.109
No, it's not about
being tough.

19:12.109 --> 19:14.362
I mean, look,
you're as tough as they come.

19:14.362 --> 19:18.282
It's just
you're...sensitive.

19:19.241 --> 19:20.409
[ Scoffs ]
You are!

19:20.409 --> 19:22.370
Look what happened
with Tamara.

19:22.370 --> 19:25.623
You gave her your car,
for crying out loud.

19:25.623 --> 19:26.957
And today ‐‐

19:26.957 --> 19:29.627
today, this whole need
to relive the last year,

19:29.627 --> 19:30.795
talk about
our feelings.

19:30.795 --> 19:33.255
I happen to think
that caring about people,

19:33.255 --> 19:36.467
connecting with them,
is what makes me a good cop.

19:36.467 --> 19:37.677
It does.

19:37.677 --> 19:39.428
Just not a good UC.

19:39.428 --> 19:41.222
Look, to work undercover,

19:41.222 --> 19:44.308
you have to be able to lie
to someone's face ‐‐

19:44.308 --> 19:45.935
make them believe
you're their best friend

19:45.935 --> 19:48.813
and then stab them
in the back.

19:48.813 --> 19:50.898
I just don't think you have
that killer instinct.

19:53.776 --> 19:55.778
Ouch.

19:55.778 --> 19:57.113
I'm sorry.

19:57.113 --> 19:58.823
But it's better
you hear it now.

19:58.823 --> 20:02.326
[ Radio chatter,
siren wailing in distance ]

20:05.663 --> 20:08.457
You're right.

20:08.457 --> 20:10.793
And I appreciate
your honesty.

20:10.793 --> 20:12.420
You always tell me
the truth,

20:12.420 --> 20:14.630
no matter how painful
it's gonna be,

20:14.630 --> 20:16.799
and you deserve the same
from me.

20:20.636 --> 20:25.599
I've been struggling with
being honest with you all day.

20:25.599 --> 20:29.645
I've been hiding behind
this stupid closure checklist,

20:29.645 --> 20:31.689
trying to get up the courage
to tell you something.

20:33.441 --> 20:34.984
Okay.

20:34.984 --> 20:36.026
What?

20:43.701 --> 20:45.327
I have feelings
for you.

20:49.790 --> 20:52.251
Uh, like f‐‐
Look, we've been through
a lot this year.

20:52.251 --> 20:56.672
I mean...
you saved my life.

20:56.672 --> 20:59.091
And I didn't want to
say anything before

20:59.091 --> 21:02.178
because I didn't want to
put you in a weird position.

21:02.178 --> 21:05.890
But now, I mean,
I think...

21:05.890 --> 21:09.477
I think the reason why you're
so protective of me and ‐‐

21:09.477 --> 21:11.562
and why you don't want me
to be an undercover cop

21:11.562 --> 21:13.063
is because...

21:15.357 --> 21:17.067
...because you have
feelings for me, too.

21:20.112 --> 21:21.405
Lucy, I ‐‐

21:21.405 --> 21:24.366
No, listen, I‐I know
it's complicated.

21:24.366 --> 21:26.076
You're my TO.

21:26.076 --> 21:28.078
You're responsible
for me.

21:28.078 --> 21:32.625
I know that you would never
cross that line, but...

21:32.625 --> 21:37.671
starting tomorrow, I guess...
you're not,

21:37.671 --> 21:39.590
and I...

21:39.590 --> 21:41.091
Uh ‐‐ Eh ‐‐

21:43.886 --> 21:45.888
First of all...

21:45.888 --> 21:47.848
I‐I just, like ‐‐

21:49.850 --> 21:50.684
Thank you.

21:50.684 --> 21:54.063
Um...you're...

21:55.397 --> 21:57.441
Look, Lucy,
I'm ‐‐ I'm flattered.

21:57.441 --> 22:00.903
I am.

22:00.903 --> 22:03.113
You're a great girl.

22:03.113 --> 22:04.782
Woman. Woman.

22:04.782 --> 22:08.744
And I...

22:08.744 --> 22:10.162
Um...

22:10.162 --> 22:11.205
[ Sighs ]

22:11.205 --> 22:13.499
Crap.

22:13.499 --> 22:14.500
Listen.

22:14.500 --> 22:17.253
[ Laughing ]

22:19.171 --> 22:21.048
Are you kidding me?!

22:21.048 --> 22:23.008
I'm sorry!

22:23.008 --> 22:23.926
Are you kidding me?

22:23.926 --> 22:25.094
Wait, I'm sorry.

22:25.094 --> 22:25.886
Oh, you're sorry.

22:25.886 --> 22:27.805
Wait. Just wait.

22:27.805 --> 22:30.057
Lie to your face ‐‐
check.

22:30.057 --> 22:31.851
Make you think
I've fallen for you ‐‐

22:31.851 --> 22:33.352
double check.

22:33.352 --> 22:35.312
Oh, and stab you
in the back

22:35.312 --> 22:36.897
when you think
we're best friends ‐‐

22:36.897 --> 22:38.399
triple check.

22:38.399 --> 22:39.775
Look me in the face...

22:39.775 --> 22:40.985
Nope.
...and tell me

22:40.985 --> 22:43.237
you don't think
I have the killer instinct

22:43.237 --> 22:45.030
to do undercover work.

22:45.030 --> 22:46.699
Look me in my face.

22:46.699 --> 22:48.117
♪♪

22:51.871 --> 22:54.915
[ Radio chatter ]

23:01.672 --> 23:04.633
It's weird now,
isn't it?

23:04.633 --> 23:05.968
Nope.

23:07.219 --> 23:09.013
I was just
making a point.

23:09.013 --> 23:11.098
And you're undermining it
by feeling guilty.

23:18.355 --> 23:19.648
Harper:
You're out of your mind.

23:19.648 --> 23:21.442
You want to try
the Camden Experiment

23:21.442 --> 23:22.526
in Los Angeles?

23:22.526 --> 23:24.069
I'm sorry. What's
the Camden Experiment?

23:24.069 --> 23:26.238
Uh, fire
all police officers,

23:26.238 --> 23:27.865
make them reapply
for their jobs.

23:27.865 --> 23:29.033
Oh, just that?

23:29.033 --> 23:31.410
[ Chuckles ]
Well, you're both good cops.

23:31.410 --> 23:33.370
You'd be back on the force
in no time.

23:33.370 --> 23:36.498
But running new background
checks on every single officer,

23:36.498 --> 23:38.792
most especially combing through
their social media posts ‐‐

23:38.792 --> 23:39.960
that'll get rid of
most of the problem.

23:39.960 --> 23:42.129
We'd be coming back to
a gutted force.

23:42.129 --> 23:44.840
I mean,
you would be down 10%.

23:44.840 --> 23:46.550
Maybe 20%.

23:46.550 --> 23:49.428
But you would be coming back to
a <i>better</i> force.

23:49.428 --> 23:50.763
And what about the kid
that goes missing

23:50.763 --> 23:52.097
the day we're all fired?

23:52.097 --> 23:54.767
I mean, it wouldn't happen
overnight.

23:54.767 --> 23:57.728
It would happen gradually,
in stages.

23:57.728 --> 24:02.107
But without major action,
things will <i>never</i> get better.

24:02.107 --> 24:03.901
Sgt. Grey: <i>7‐Adam‐15,</i>

24:03.901 --> 24:05.736
<i>we have a possible suspect ID</i>
<i>on the Amber Alert.</i>

24:05.736 --> 24:08.072
<i>Last name Cissane,</i>
<i>first name Rita.</i>

24:08.072 --> 24:10.240
<i>Suspect's husband called 911.</i>

24:10.240 --> 24:12.117
<i>Make contact</i>
<i>to take his statement.</i>

24:12.117 --> 24:14.161
<i>Address is being sent</i>
<i>to your box.</i>

24:14.161 --> 24:16.121
Copy that. We got it.
On our way.

24:18.582 --> 24:20.876
Ethan: Yeah, if, uh ‐‐
i‐if she reaches out,

24:20.876 --> 24:24.463
um, please, please,
please, please call me.

24:24.463 --> 24:27.007
Um...okay. Yeah, no.
I‐I gotta go.

24:30.177 --> 24:32.304
Mr. Cissane,
I'm Detective Harper.

24:32.304 --> 24:33.931
This is Officer Nolan.

24:33.931 --> 24:37.226
I understand that your wife,
Rita, was here with a baby?

24:37.226 --> 24:39.269
Yeah, I‐I don't ‐‐
I don't know where she is.

24:39.269 --> 24:42.815
I‐I tried calling
everyone that I know.

24:42.815 --> 24:44.566
I‐I tried to stop her
from leaving,

24:44.566 --> 24:48.278
but she was holding that baby,
and it was...just so little.

24:48.278 --> 24:51.031
I know. They can look
so fragile at that age.

24:51.031 --> 24:52.366
Uh, tell us about
your wife.

24:52.366 --> 24:54.827
Is there anything that could
have precipitated this?

24:54.827 --> 24:57.705
You don't know?

24:57.705 --> 25:02.334
W‐We lost our daughter, Casey,
this morning to SIDS.

25:02.334 --> 25:05.337
Rita went into the nursery
to check on her,

25:05.337 --> 25:08.841
and then I heard screaming,
so I ran in,

25:08.841 --> 25:13.429
and she was so still...
s‐so cold.

25:13.429 --> 25:16.849
I am so sorry.
Sir, h‐how old was she?

25:16.849 --> 25:18.392
[ Crying ] Two months.

25:18.392 --> 25:20.686
That's why your wife was
at the hospital today?

25:20.686 --> 25:23.230
Yeah, we ‐‐ we raced Casey
to the Emergency Room,

25:23.230 --> 25:25.399
hoping that they could do
something, but it was ‐‐

25:25.399 --> 25:27.192
it was too late.

25:27.192 --> 25:31.905
And then there was so many, uh,
questions and ‐‐ and forms.

25:31.905 --> 25:36.118
It took me a while to realize
that, um, that Rita had left.

25:36.118 --> 25:38.245
She wasn't answering her cell,
so I thought maybe s‐she ‐‐

25:38.245 --> 25:40.706
she came home,
but she wasn't here,

25:40.706 --> 25:43.417
and then she just showed up
like nothing had happened,

25:43.417 --> 25:46.795
and she was just...
holding this little baby

25:46.795 --> 25:49.423
and calling her Casey

25:49.423 --> 25:50.758
and saying that everything had
been a big mistake.

25:50.758 --> 25:51.800
[ Sniffles ]

25:51.800 --> 25:53.469
Okay, uh, we're gonna
have to initiate

25:53.469 --> 25:55.262
Child Death Protocol.

25:55.262 --> 25:56.680
Treat the place
like a crime scene.

25:56.680 --> 26:00.434
Notify Homicide,
the District Attorney, and CPS.

26:00.434 --> 26:02.352
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
We didn't kill our daughter.

26:02.352 --> 26:03.270
It was ‐‐ It was ‐‐
It was SIDS.

26:03.270 --> 26:05.439
Yes, sir.
I understand.

26:05.439 --> 26:07.649
I'm not saying that we believe
that you harmed your child,

26:07.649 --> 26:09.610
but we do have protocols
we have to follow.

26:09.610 --> 26:11.695
Eh, sir, it's ‐‐
the hard fact is

26:11.695 --> 26:13.530
what most people consider
to be SIDS

26:13.530 --> 26:16.200
is actually accidental
suffocation

26:16.200 --> 26:18.660
from soft bedding
or a toy.

26:18.660 --> 26:21.872
Uh, right now, we have to
focus on your wife.

26:21.872 --> 26:23.749
Is there anywhere you think
she might have gone?

26:23.749 --> 26:24.958
I don't know.

26:24.958 --> 26:26.293
I've reached out to everyone
I can think of,

26:26.293 --> 26:28.962
but she's not really
herself right ‐‐ right now.

26:28.962 --> 26:31.006
Has she been depressed
lately?

26:31.006 --> 26:33.217
Yeah. I mean, she hasn't been
eating or sleeping.

26:33.217 --> 26:36.011
The doctor said she had,
um...PPD,

26:36.011 --> 26:38.055
but Rita refused any help.

26:38.055 --> 26:39.932
Uh, has she been
drinking a lot?

26:39.932 --> 26:41.433
Any drugs
or medication?
No.

26:41.433 --> 26:43.811
No, the doctor prescribed
antidepressants,

26:43.811 --> 26:46.271
but Rita wouldn't take them.
I'm just so scared that ‐‐

26:46.271 --> 26:47.981
Thank you, sir.
Okay, thank you.

26:47.981 --> 26:49.650
Please don't hurt her.

26:49.650 --> 26:51.193
She's not herself right now.
[ Car doors open, close ]

26:51.193 --> 26:53.028
You have to promise me that
you won't hurt her, please.

26:54.530 --> 26:56.031
[ Engine starts ]

26:56.031 --> 26:58.367
[ Sobbing ]

26:58.367 --> 27:02.246
♪♪

27:06.667 --> 27:08.585
Updated Amber Alert.

27:08.585 --> 27:10.838
New suspect vehicle is
a green Ford Fiesta.

27:10.838 --> 27:14.466
License plate
3‐Paul‐Charles‐Ida‐0‐2‐6.

27:14.466 --> 27:16.593
Suspect is Rita Cissane.

27:16.593 --> 27:19.638
31‐year‐old white female
who lost her baby to SIDS.

27:23.433 --> 27:25.853
This case is all the nightmares
in my closet combined.

27:25.853 --> 27:28.272
I know. Sorry.

27:28.272 --> 27:30.482
How am I ever gonna let my kid
out of my sight?

27:30.482 --> 27:32.484
With all the things we see
on the job,

27:32.484 --> 27:33.902
the ‐‐ the things I know
about people ‐‐

27:33.902 --> 27:36.697
Look, the things we see
are outliers.

27:36.697 --> 27:39.908
Look, every day, we show up
on people's worst day.

27:39.908 --> 27:42.035
We see the exception,
not the rule.

27:42.035 --> 27:44.705
I know that up here,
but ‐‐

27:44.705 --> 27:48.834
Look, whether the kid is with
you or Wesley or a nanny,

27:48.834 --> 27:50.419
they'll be fine, okay?

27:50.419 --> 27:53.255
It's just so different
from the way I grew up.

27:53.255 --> 27:55.549
Wesley was raised
by a nanny.

27:55.549 --> 27:59.303
But when my mom went to work,
she put me in the back room,

27:59.303 --> 28:02.472
and the other women
would check in on me.

28:02.472 --> 28:05.475
Can't exactly drop off Lopez Jr.
in Holding every morning.

28:05.475 --> 28:06.977
[ Chuckles ]
I don't know.

28:06.977 --> 28:08.854
Smitty is
surprisingly maternal.

28:08.854 --> 28:10.439
[ Chuckles ]

28:10.439 --> 28:13.275
That is the most horrifying idea
I've ever heard...

28:13.275 --> 28:15.360
and I want it to be
a reality show so bad.

28:15.360 --> 28:17.613
Right? I would watch
the hell out of that.

28:18.572 --> 28:21.158
Rita is negative
on any previous 5150 holds,

28:21.158 --> 28:23.619
and there are no registered
firearms in her name.

28:23.619 --> 28:24.912
If this woman's doctor couldn't
get through to her,

28:24.912 --> 28:26.204
how will you?

28:26.204 --> 28:27.331
I‐I mean,
this woman is in crisis.

28:27.331 --> 28:28.790
She needs a psychiatrist.

28:28.790 --> 28:30.042
Yeah, but the baby
needs a cop.

28:30.042 --> 28:32.294
The honest truth is we
don't have enough information

28:32.294 --> 28:33.670
to know what
we're dealing with.

28:33.670 --> 28:35.255
But that's every call.

28:35.255 --> 28:36.924
It's a constant struggle
to figure things out

28:36.924 --> 28:38.425
before it's too late.

28:40.886 --> 28:42.930
Uh, 7‐Adam‐19,
go to channel nine.

28:43.889 --> 28:45.557
Go for 7‐Adam‐19.

28:45.557 --> 28:47.309
Did you study
postpartum depression

28:47.309 --> 28:48.560
in your psych major?

28:48.560 --> 28:53.148
Yeah. PPD is fairly common,
affects 1 in 8 new moms.

28:53.148 --> 28:55.692
<i>In most cases, they feel tired,</i>
<i>alone, guilty.</i>

28:55.692 --> 28:57.319
Some feel a lack of attachment
and then guilt

28:57.319 --> 28:58.654
for not feeling attached.

28:58.654 --> 29:02.658
<i>Some are overwhelmed</i>
<i>by paranoia ‐‐</i>

29:02.658 --> 29:06.995
visions of horrible things
happening to their own child.

29:06.995 --> 29:09.748
I see Rita turned down
treatment.

29:09.748 --> 29:12.042
<i>That tells me she's probably</i>
<i>dealing with shame,</i>

29:12.042 --> 29:14.169
trying to cope alone,
isolating.

29:14.169 --> 29:15.754
Now add to that
the trauma

29:15.754 --> 29:18.048
of finding her child
unresponsive.

29:18.048 --> 29:19.883
That could precipitate
a mental break.

29:19.883 --> 29:22.135
If it's an extreme case of PPD,
which is rare,

29:22.135 --> 29:24.930
she could be thinking about
harming herself or her baby.

29:24.930 --> 29:26.223
Tim. Green Fiesta.

29:26.223 --> 29:27.391
Plates match.
That's our car.

29:27.391 --> 29:28.433
Nolan, we found
Rita's car.

29:28.433 --> 29:31.103
21000 block of Manningham.

29:31.103 --> 29:33.271
On our way.
Let's go.

29:33.271 --> 29:35.273
♪♪

29:37.776 --> 29:39.152
Lucy: Control, 7‐Adam‐19,

29:39.152 --> 29:41.655
we've located the Fiesta from
the revised Amber Alert.

29:41.655 --> 29:44.241
21000 block of Manningham.

29:44.241 --> 29:46.201
[ <i>Pleasant music plays</i>
<i>on stereo</i> ]
No sign of suspect or child.

29:48.996 --> 29:51.039
It's still hot.
She must have just ditched it.

29:51.039 --> 29:53.000
Man: Hey. You looking
for the driver?

29:53.000 --> 29:54.459
Tim: Yeah, you see
where she went?

29:54.459 --> 29:56.712
Nah. I was walking by
when she parked on the curb.

29:56.712 --> 29:58.714
How long ago?
About five minutes.

29:58.714 --> 30:00.173
Enough time for Butch and I
to circle the block.

30:00.173 --> 30:02.676
Did she have
a baby with her?
No idea.

30:02.676 --> 30:05.220
I just watched her
totally demolish
that parking spot.

30:05.220 --> 30:06.888
[ Laughs ] Reminded me
of my ex‐wife.

30:06.888 --> 30:08.557
Uh, yes, sir.
Please call us

30:08.557 --> 30:10.475
if you remember
anything else.
Okay.

30:10.475 --> 30:12.769
Control, 7‐Adam‐19, I got
the vehicle, unoccupied.

30:12.769 --> 30:14.771
Witness says the suspect here
less than five minutes ago.

30:14.771 --> 30:15.981
She's on foot.

30:15.981 --> 30:17.315
We need backup
and an airship

30:17.315 --> 30:18.400
to secure
a 10‐block radius

30:18.400 --> 30:19.609
for a grid search.

30:21.194 --> 30:22.571
♪♪

30:22.571 --> 30:23.655
I don't like this.

30:23.655 --> 30:24.740
She wouldn't have abandoned
the car

30:24.740 --> 30:26.241
unless she stopped
for a reason.

30:26.241 --> 30:27.909
Odds are it won't be
a good one.

30:27.909 --> 30:29.536
We gotta find her fast.

30:33.331 --> 30:35.375
This is crazy.

30:35.375 --> 30:36.752
There's no way we find her
and the baby in time.

30:36.752 --> 30:38.879
We've got multiple units
and an airship searching.

30:38.879 --> 30:39.713
We will find them.

30:39.713 --> 30:41.173
How? They could be
anywhere.

30:41.173 --> 30:43.508
No. On foot with a newborn
and a five‐minute head start,

30:43.508 --> 30:45.177
she's definitely within
our grid.

30:45.177 --> 30:46.470
Someone will have seen her.

30:46.470 --> 30:50.057
Just...pray we find her before
she does something rash.

30:50.057 --> 30:59.357
♪♪

30:59.357 --> 31:00.442
Up on the right.

31:00.442 --> 31:02.694
[ Siren chirps ]

31:04.696 --> 31:06.740
Not her.

31:09.910 --> 31:11.119
Can I make a suggestion?

31:11.119 --> 31:12.537
Of course.

31:12.537 --> 31:14.414
Would it be helpful to have
Rita's husband

31:14.414 --> 31:17.626
brought down here
for ‐‐ for when she's found?

31:17.626 --> 31:19.127
That could be
dangerous.

31:19.127 --> 31:21.129
We don't know what the situation
was like at the house,

31:21.129 --> 31:23.632
and even if the baby's death
truly was accidental,

31:23.632 --> 31:25.425
there could have been
marital issues

31:25.425 --> 31:27.094
that added to Rita's PPD.

31:27.094 --> 31:28.804
We'd be introducing
a wildcard

31:28.804 --> 31:30.138
to an already tenuous
situation.

31:30.138 --> 31:31.765
Wait, so it's all on you?

31:31.765 --> 31:33.975
I mean, no matter what you find
when you get to her,

31:33.975 --> 31:35.102
you have to be ready to
deal with it?

31:35.102 --> 31:37.771
What ‐‐ What if you make
a mistake?

31:37.771 --> 31:39.648
We have to live with it.

31:39.648 --> 31:42.234
If we can.

31:42.234 --> 31:44.861
Pilot: <i>All units, Air Three has</i>
<i>eyes on the suspect.</i>

31:44.861 --> 31:45.946
Fourth Street Bridge.

31:45.946 --> 31:48.698
Repeat ‐‐
Fourth Street Bridge.

31:48.698 --> 31:50.909
She has the baby.
She's standing at the railing.

31:50.909 --> 31:53.453
Possible jumper.
Repeat, possible jumper.

31:53.453 --> 31:54.621
Here we go.

31:54.621 --> 31:56.873
Control, advise Fire we have
a possible jumper

31:56.873 --> 31:57.958
on Fourth Street Bridge.

31:57.958 --> 31:59.251
See if they have
a crash pad available.

31:59.251 --> 32:02.629
We'll also need RA and
backup units, Code 2 high.

32:02.629 --> 32:08.969
♪♪

32:08.969 --> 32:11.847
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

32:15.100 --> 32:16.977
[ Car doors close ]

32:16.977 --> 32:18.895
Maybe I should
stay back.

32:18.895 --> 32:20.313
Uh, it's up to you,

32:20.313 --> 32:21.731
but a friendly face
not in uniform

32:21.731 --> 32:23.483
might actually calm
the situation.

32:23.483 --> 32:24.943
How do you want to
play this?

32:24.943 --> 32:25.694
You go talk to her.

32:25.694 --> 32:26.987
You sure?

32:26.987 --> 32:28.572
Yeah, I'll step in
if I need to.

32:31.241 --> 32:34.202
W‐Why ‐‐ Why Nolan?

32:34.202 --> 32:37.831
He has a way of connecting with
people in crisis situations.

32:37.831 --> 32:40.208
Hi, Rita.

32:40.208 --> 32:41.251
I'm John.

32:41.251 --> 32:42.252
[ Baby crying ]

32:42.252 --> 32:43.837
How do you know
my name?

32:43.837 --> 32:45.213
Uh, Ethan told me.

32:45.213 --> 32:47.674
He's very worried
about you.

32:47.674 --> 32:49.593
I'm fine.

32:49.593 --> 32:51.553
Who's that
you got there?

32:51.553 --> 32:52.888
Casey.

32:52.888 --> 32:54.181
This is Casey.

32:54.181 --> 32:55.640
Oh.

32:55.640 --> 32:57.309
Casey looks
a little bit cold.

32:57.309 --> 32:59.269
Why don't we bring her inside,
off the bridge?

32:59.269 --> 33:00.187
No.

33:00.187 --> 33:02.731
She's fine with
her mama.

33:02.731 --> 33:04.816
Do you mind if I just
make sure?

33:04.816 --> 33:06.026
Stay back.

33:06.026 --> 33:07.068
Okay, yeah.
I'll stay back.

33:07.068 --> 33:08.361
We ‐‐ We can just talk.

33:16.995 --> 33:17.829
Lucy: How's she doing?

33:17.829 --> 33:19.915
Uh, it's touch and go.

33:19.915 --> 33:21.583
What do you need?
Keep them back.

33:21.583 --> 33:23.293
We don't want to
spook her.

33:23.293 --> 33:25.295
Okay.
Nolan: No, I know it can
feel isolating,

33:25.295 --> 33:27.047
being a parent to
a newborn...

33:27.047 --> 33:28.173
She's not looking at
the baby.

33:28.173 --> 33:29.925
Nolan:
...so much to learn.

33:29.925 --> 33:31.593
[ Baby fusses ]
You never feel like
what you're doing...

33:31.593 --> 33:33.178
She's trying to
convince herself

33:33.178 --> 33:34.930
that it's her baby
she's holding.

33:34.930 --> 33:37.515
Yeah. Deep down inside,
she knows it's not.

33:37.515 --> 33:39.601
What happens when
she figures out the truth?

33:39.601 --> 33:41.186
It's hard to say
for sure.

33:41.186 --> 33:42.812
It could break the spell or it
could send her over the edge,

33:42.812 --> 33:44.189
literally.

33:44.189 --> 33:45.982
Control, what's the ETA
on Fire?

33:45.982 --> 33:47.234
Dispatch: <i>Three minutes.</i>

33:47.234 --> 33:48.818
Might as well be
three hours.

33:48.818 --> 33:51.196
Nolan: Are you thirsty,
Rita?

33:51.196 --> 33:51.905
I can get you
some water.

33:51.905 --> 33:53.448
Nolan.

33:53.448 --> 33:54.950
Can I talk to her?

33:54.950 --> 33:56.117
Hey, Rita, I'm gonna
introduce you

33:56.117 --> 33:57.619
to my friend,
Angela, okay?

33:57.619 --> 33:59.120
Okay.

33:59.120 --> 34:00.580
Hi, Rita.

34:00.580 --> 34:02.666
I'm here to help.

34:02.666 --> 34:03.708
Is this Casey?

34:05.001 --> 34:06.586
Yes.

34:06.586 --> 34:08.088
I love that name.

34:08.088 --> 34:11.925
My fiancé and I can't agree
on a name for our baby.

34:11.925 --> 34:13.510
How did you choose?

34:13.510 --> 34:15.720
I don't know.

34:15.720 --> 34:17.847
When she was born, she just
looked like a Casey.

34:17.847 --> 34:20.684
[ Baby fussing ]

34:20.684 --> 34:22.352
How far along are you?

34:22.352 --> 34:24.104
14 weeks.

34:24.104 --> 34:26.773
I'm already scared
about giving birth.

34:26.773 --> 34:27.941
The pain.

34:27.941 --> 34:30.235
Don't worry about
the pain.

34:30.235 --> 34:33.947
Once they put your baby
in your arms

34:33.947 --> 34:37.367
and you look down into
those beautiful eyes,

34:37.367 --> 34:39.202
it was all worth it.

34:39.202 --> 34:42.706
I heard all newborns
have blue eyes.

34:42.706 --> 34:44.249
Not Casey.

34:44.249 --> 34:47.585
Dark brown,
right from the start.

34:47.585 --> 34:50.380
The most amazing
head of hair.

34:50.380 --> 34:51.256
I hope
if I have a daughter,

34:51.256 --> 34:53.049
she's born with hair.

34:53.049 --> 34:56.052
My cousin's little girl,
she was bald

34:56.052 --> 34:58.096
for like the first
18 months.

34:58.096 --> 34:59.723
Everyone thought
she was a boy.

34:59.723 --> 35:01.016
I love putting

35:01.016 --> 35:03.476
Casey's hair
in little pigtails.

35:03.476 --> 35:07.397
She always fights me,
but she looks so cute.

35:07.397 --> 35:11.776
Rita, can you do something
for me?

35:11.776 --> 35:13.403
Can you look at Casey?

35:13.403 --> 35:15.530
Just look in those pretty,
brown eyes.

35:15.530 --> 35:18.033
[ Baby crying ]

35:18.033 --> 35:19.075
No.

35:19.075 --> 35:20.243
Please, Rita.

35:20.243 --> 35:21.995
I need you to
look in her eyes.

35:21.995 --> 35:24.039
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

35:27.500 --> 35:30.128
[ Crying continues ]

35:31.963 --> 35:35.550
It's not Casey,
is it?

35:35.550 --> 35:37.552
[ Voice breaking ] No.

35:37.552 --> 35:39.721
No.

35:39.721 --> 35:42.390
Here. I got her.

35:42.390 --> 35:45.060
I'll get her back to
her mother, okay?

35:48.688 --> 35:51.066
Tell her [Sniffles]
I'm sorry.

35:53.276 --> 35:54.694
Nolan:
Thank you, Rita.

35:54.694 --> 35:56.905
That was a very brave thing
you did,

35:56.905 --> 35:58.907
and now I need you
to come with me, okay?

36:00.200 --> 36:02.535
My baby died.

36:02.535 --> 36:03.995
I know.

36:03.995 --> 36:05.163
I'm so sorry.

36:05.163 --> 36:07.332
[ Sobbing ]

36:07.332 --> 36:11.169
Come on. Come on.

36:13.088 --> 36:15.590
[ Baby cooing ]

36:15.590 --> 36:22.889
♪♪

36:28.812 --> 36:31.356
[ Engine shuts off ]

36:31.356 --> 36:33.316
Well, thank you
for today.

36:33.316 --> 36:35.610
This is an experience
I will not forget.

36:35.610 --> 36:37.737
Well, we should schedule

36:37.737 --> 36:39.698
another one of these
little ride alongs

36:39.698 --> 36:41.533
so that we can continue
the conversation.

36:41.533 --> 36:43.159
Oh, that won't be
necessary.

36:43.159 --> 36:44.285
[ Camera clicks off ]

36:44.285 --> 36:46.830
The book's already written,
isn't it?

36:46.830 --> 36:48.707
I sent it to my publisher
last week.

36:48.707 --> 36:50.208
Mm.
What?

36:50.208 --> 36:51.668
Then what was today about,
then?

36:51.668 --> 36:53.753
Just an anecdote
for the book tour?

36:53.753 --> 36:56.172
No, I didn't know the day was
gonna end up the way it did.

36:56.172 --> 36:58.133
But how do you write a book
about policing

36:58.133 --> 36:59.217
without having seen it
up close?

36:59.217 --> 37:01.219
Oh, I have seen it.
Believe me.

37:01.219 --> 37:02.721
Today may have been
my first ride along,

37:02.721 --> 37:03.805
but it was not my first time

37:03.805 --> 37:05.390
sitting in the back seat
of a cop car.

37:05.390 --> 37:07.726
I see, but if you're going to
fix an engine,

37:07.726 --> 37:09.394
don't you think it would be
helpful to look under the hood?

37:09.394 --> 37:11.604
That is a flawed analogy,
Officer Nolan,

37:11.604 --> 37:13.148
because a car is not
actively trying to

37:13.148 --> 37:14.315
keep you from fixing it.

37:15.692 --> 37:17.068
Uh, excuse me.

37:19.362 --> 37:22.407
Look, I get that the path
to real change

37:22.407 --> 37:24.409
seems almost impossible.

37:24.409 --> 37:27.370
I mean, police departments are
pros at circling the wagons

37:27.370 --> 37:29.914
when public opinion
turns against them.

37:29.914 --> 37:32.667
But I promise you,

37:32.667 --> 37:35.003
the only way
things really will change

37:35.003 --> 37:37.422
is if cops get on board.

37:37.422 --> 37:38.757
I agree.

37:38.757 --> 37:41.301
But cops only act when activists
make so much noise,

37:41.301 --> 37:42.886
they cannot be ignored.

37:42.886 --> 37:44.429
Like in Camden.

37:44.429 --> 37:46.765
Look, you're talking to
two police officers

37:46.765 --> 37:48.308
who would like to
see things change,

37:48.308 --> 37:51.436
and we're not the only ones at
the station that feels this way.

37:51.436 --> 37:54.981
I just think that...
uh, maybe you could benefit

37:54.981 --> 37:57.358
from some of our insights.

38:01.529 --> 38:02.405
Alright.

38:03.615 --> 38:05.325
You sold me.

38:05.325 --> 38:07.327
Great.
I'll tell Sergeant Grey.

38:07.327 --> 38:08.870
I'm sure he'd love to
be part of the conversation.

38:08.870 --> 38:10.497
Oh, thank you.

38:10.497 --> 38:13.333
And thank you both for
the ride along.

38:13.333 --> 38:14.876
I will see you in class.

38:14.876 --> 38:16.169
Looking forward.

38:19.297 --> 38:22.217
I think that went well,
all things considered.

38:22.217 --> 38:24.385
Oh, yeah. No, she's definitely
gonna give you an "A."

38:24.385 --> 38:26.221
‐You think?
‐No.

38:26.221 --> 38:27.972
She is gonna make you earn it
in class,

38:27.972 --> 38:29.307
like the rest of
her students.

38:29.307 --> 38:30.809
Fair enough.
Yeah.

38:30.809 --> 38:32.310
You have any plans for
the rest of the night?

38:32.310 --> 38:34.521
Hugging my daughter
until she is sick of it

38:34.521 --> 38:36.564
and then hugging her
some more.
Sounds nice.

38:36.564 --> 38:37.524
Nolan.

38:39.150 --> 38:40.735
I'll see you tomorrow.
Alright.

38:40.735 --> 38:42.570
Sir.
Well?

38:42.570 --> 38:44.197
How'd it go
with Professor Ryan?

38:44.197 --> 38:45.657
Good, I think.

38:45.657 --> 38:47.659
She's gonna be calling you to
talk about, uh, police reform ‐‐

38:47.659 --> 38:48.910
for her book.

38:48.910 --> 38:51.037
[ Chuckles ]

38:51.037 --> 38:53.414
You point her my way to get back
at me for the ride along?

38:53.414 --> 38:54.415
No, sir. No.

38:54.415 --> 38:55.416
I just know
how committed you are

38:55.416 --> 38:57.460
to making things better.

38:57.460 --> 38:59.879
Even if it does mean having to
admit you're wrong to do it.

38:59.879 --> 39:01.965
Oh. Uh, I'm sorry?

39:03.091 --> 39:05.301
When was I ever wrong?

39:05.301 --> 39:08.596
Well, nothing comes to
mind off hand.

39:08.596 --> 39:11.391
I guess there was that one time
you said if I succeeded,

39:11.391 --> 39:13.935
your house would be
"flooded with middle‐aged losers

39:13.935 --> 39:18.189
looking for an 'Eat Pray Love'
path to reinvention."

39:18.189 --> 39:20.483
I wrote it down.

39:20.483 --> 39:23.486
You haven't succeeded yet,
Officer Nolan.

39:23.486 --> 39:25.864
Yes, sir.

39:25.864 --> 39:26.614
Good night, sir.

39:26.614 --> 39:29.075
Good night.

39:29.075 --> 39:31.035
Lopez: Can't wait to get out
of this uniform.

39:31.035 --> 39:32.579
Hey, thanks again for
riding with me.

39:32.579 --> 39:33.788
Are you kidding me?

39:33.788 --> 39:35.540
I wouldn't have missed it
for the world.

39:35.540 --> 39:37.959
And now
it's end of shift,

39:37.959 --> 39:40.420
and you are no longer
a rookie.

39:40.420 --> 39:41.880
[ Exhales deeply ]

39:41.880 --> 39:43.548
How does it feel?

39:43.548 --> 39:45.592
Unreal.

39:45.592 --> 39:47.719
I mean, everything in my life
has been geared towards

39:47.719 --> 39:52.223
getting me to this moment,
and...now it's here.

39:52.223 --> 39:53.975
Kinda can't believe it,
to be honest.

39:53.975 --> 39:57.145
Well, congratulations.

39:57.145 --> 39:58.813
You earned it.

39:58.813 --> 40:00.148
♪ I couldn't see the forest
for the trees ♪

40:00.148 --> 40:03.109
♪ Too many empties on the side ♪

40:03.109 --> 40:05.570
♪ But I kept trading all
my cigarettes for sunsets ♪

40:05.570 --> 40:06.613
♪ Now I'm getting richer
all the time ♪

40:06.613 --> 40:08.489
We did it.

40:08.489 --> 40:10.325
No. <i>You</i> did it.

40:12.994 --> 40:14.579
What's this?

40:14.579 --> 40:17.206
It's a copy of
your final evaluation.

40:17.206 --> 40:19.042
I wrote it
before our shift today.

40:19.042 --> 40:21.461
Like Plain Clothes Day.

40:21.461 --> 40:23.421
Only this time,
I didn't have to rewrite it.

40:23.421 --> 40:25.089
Mm.

40:25.089 --> 40:26.382
♪ I'll be young before I die ♪

40:26.382 --> 40:28.051
"Officer Chen impressed me

40:28.051 --> 40:30.094
with every decision she made
today.

40:30.094 --> 40:32.221
I will miss
riding with her."

40:32.221 --> 40:33.932
♪ I'll be wrong before
I'm right ♪

40:33.932 --> 40:37.477
♪ I keep filling up
my crowded heart, yeah ♪

40:37.477 --> 40:39.812
You don't let anyone
ever tell you

40:39.812 --> 40:42.065
you can't do something.

40:42.065 --> 40:43.816
Not even me.

40:43.816 --> 40:45.401
♪ Now all I see is the beauty
of the thunderstorm ♪

40:45.401 --> 40:46.819
Yes, sir.

40:46.819 --> 40:47.904
♪ Let it wash it all away ♪
[ Inhales deeply ]

40:47.904 --> 40:51.324
Step five ‐‐ acceptance.

40:51.324 --> 40:54.118
Our checklist is complete.
[ Chuckles ]

40:54.118 --> 40:56.454
Um...I have
a gift for you.

40:57.830 --> 41:00.375
It's a thank‐you.

41:00.375 --> 41:02.752
For every lesson
I had to learn.

41:02.752 --> 41:05.380
Uh, should I open it now?

41:05.380 --> 41:06.589
Absolutely.

41:06.589 --> 41:07.340
Mm‐hmm.

41:07.340 --> 41:08.591
Okay.

41:08.591 --> 41:10.051
♪ I'll be dumb before I'm wise ♪

41:10.051 --> 41:11.803
[ Pop ]

41:11.803 --> 41:13.179
♪ I'll be wrong
before I'm right ♪
[ Chuckles ]

41:13.179 --> 41:14.347
[ Exhales sharply ]

41:14.347 --> 41:16.933
[ Laughs ]
It's been a blast, sir.

41:16.933 --> 41:19.852
I'll see you tomorrow...Lucy.

41:21.020 --> 41:23.022
See you tomorrow, Tim.
[ Door opens ]

41:23.022 --> 41:24.607
♪ I will laugh and I will cry ♪
[ Door closes ]

41:24.607 --> 41:26.442
[ Chuckles ]

41:26.442 --> 41:27.485
Ready to celebrate?

41:27.485 --> 41:29.445
You know it.
[ Chuckles ]

41:29.445 --> 41:33.491
So, yeah. It was
the perfect way to end the year.

41:33.491 --> 41:34.701
[ Indistinct conversation ]

41:34.701 --> 41:35.702
Exactly.

41:35.702 --> 41:37.120
Where you going?

41:38.621 --> 41:40.540
Uh, home.

41:40.540 --> 41:42.500
No, you're not.

41:42.500 --> 41:44.585
You are coming to dinner
with Lila and me.

41:44.585 --> 41:47.088
Uh, that's ‐‐ that's very nice
of you, but I'm okay.

41:47.088 --> 41:48.673
No, you're not.

41:48.673 --> 41:50.758
You feel like a failure
because they're moving on

41:50.758 --> 41:52.593
and you're not.

41:52.593 --> 41:54.846
But you will.

41:54.846 --> 41:56.389
I appreciate that,
but you, uh,

41:56.389 --> 41:58.725
certainly don't have to take me
to dinner out of pity.

41:58.725 --> 42:00.935
It's not pity
when you're paying.

42:00.935 --> 42:02.228
♪ I'll keep filling up... ♪

42:02.228 --> 42:03.855
W‐Well, how can I say no
to that?

42:03.855 --> 42:05.773
You can't.

42:05.773 --> 42:07.483
I'm gonna go pick up
Lila.

42:07.483 --> 42:10.403
Reservation is under my name
at Mercado.

42:10.403 --> 42:12.989
And I expect a skinny margarita
waiting when I get there.

42:12.989 --> 42:13.865
Yes, ma'am.
Mm‐hmm.

42:13.865 --> 42:15.908
And, um...

42:15.908 --> 42:16.909
Thank you.

42:16.909 --> 42:18.077
You're welcome.

42:19.829 --> 42:20.329
[ Car door closes ]

42:27.378 --> 42:33.426
♪♪

42:33.426 --> 42:39.432
♪♪

42:39.432 --> 42:45.480
♪♪

42:45.480 --> 42:51.360
♪♪
